    "benchmark_id": "networkx",
    "description": "Pure graph-algorithm subset modelled on the networkx library, over an undirected weighted graph Graph := List (Nat × Nat × Nat). Two complementary modules. Components: numConnectedComponents/sameComponent/componentOf — the partition of the nodes into maximal mutually-reachable sets; the obligations pin sameComponent to be the undirected-connectivity equivalence (reflexivity, edge-coherence, symmetry, transitivity, walk-soundness, and component-closure/maximality), and componentOf to be exactly the equivalence class, anchored on a frozen undirected-walk notion (uEdge/isUWalk). Mst: mstWeight/numTreeEdges/subsetWeight — the least total weight of a spanning forest; the headline obligation set is witness ∧ minimality ∧ exact-optimum on mstWeight, anchored on a frozen ground-truth spanning-forest notion (spanningForest = sub-multiset of edges + same-component-partition + acyclic forest edge-count identity, forestWeight = edge-weight sum): the returned weight is realized by an actual spanning forest and is no larger than any spanning forest's weight, so it is pinned to the genuine minimum-spanning-tree weight (a UNIQUE optimum). The reference impls are spec-shaped (fixed-point reachability closure for connectivity; brute-force minimum over all spanning-forest subsets for the MST weight) so soundness is a clean min?-fact, while any real impl (Kruskal/Borůvka/Prim, union-find, BFS) must hit the same optimum. Scope: undirected connectivity and minimum-spanning-forest WEIGHT only — no returned tree edge sequence, mstWeight is a single Nat, edge weights are nonnegative Nat, an edge (u,v,w) connects u and v in either direction. Distinct from the directed single-pair shortest-path-cost dijkstar benchmark and the layered Kahn toposort benchmark.",
